          "body": "Luke 3:21-22 is one of the New Testament's clearest trinitarian moments. The Son submits to baptism (identifying with sinners, though He has none of His own); the Spirit descends bodily, like a dove; the Father speaks from heaven, *You are My beloved Son, in You I am well-pleased*. Three persons, one action, one unified self-revelation. Luke uniquely notes that Jesus was *praying* (3:21) when heaven opened — Luke's recurring pattern of Jesus at prayer at every major hinge (5:16; 6:12; 9:18, 28-29; 11:1; 22:41). The Father's words combine Psalm 2:7 (*You are My Son*, royal-messianic) with Isaiah 42:1 (*My chosen, in whom My soul delights*, suffering-servant). King and Servant in one Son."
